Analysis of documentation has been done.
A diagram of flows between the systems has been enhanced with the new requirements.
Rough estimations have been provided for delivery of each functionality.

Architect notes:
- I took a look at the documentation and I've attached my notes to this story
- use the Draw.io web application to create mockups and diagrams of how the systems will communicate
- define individual tasks which need to be done in order for us to deliver this project; include time for testing and also some time for fixing and some reserves

]]> true false not requested ca8c03c0932b02100580f55a7bba10e7 product false automatic Feature false Hello, we are a company selling lots of different products and we have a small team of technical and process people managing our services and systems. We are currently managing our ServiceNow instance and an external System called System X. Both of these systems are used by different teams of people for ticketing purposes. In order to centralize this process and enable more of the advanced functionality provided to us by ServiceNow, we would like you to help us implement eBonding between these 2 systems. We will provide you with a documentation of our systems, which is a little bit outdated, but should help jump start your understanding of where we are right now. We would like you to work out a general overview of steps which need to be taken and provide us with a rough estimate. This will be used to plan the project and to deal with resources. We have hired your team, which consists of a developer and an architect, to deliver this project within a reasonable time frame. Our technical and process team will assist you as best as they can (if they are not on vacation). We will develop in an agile way using 2 week sprints, daily stand up meetings and sprint review and sprint planning meetings. The goal of each sprint is to deliver a finished product into Production. The end goal is for our ServiceNow instance and our System X to seamlessly synchronize tickets and their changes. Architect commentary: - kick off meetings are often organised at or before the start of a project with the goal to introduce everyone critical for the project success and to plan the next steps ahead as well as to highlight the most important parts of the project - sometimes we provide a whole team to a customer, sometimes our employees integrate with an already existing team from the customer's side - having documentation at all can sometimes be a blessing, but having it up to date is even more rare - interfaces and eBonding in particular could become quite complex, so we should be careful on making early judgments about the complexity and effort needed here - I will be providing you with pointers as much as my time allows it (it can happen that important people on the project are only available to you for a limited time, make sure to use that time well) - at times the customer requires some sort of rough estimations even though we are still missing a lot of critical information ->
